        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1966-01-08T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1966-01-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="525"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d525">
                <head>525. Note From the President’s Deputy Special Assistant for National Security
                    Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_KRW2" type="from">Komer</persName>) to the
                    President’s Special Assistant for National Security Affairs (<persName
                        corresp="#p_BMG2" type="to">Bundy</persName>)<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d525fn1">Source: Johnson Library, National Security File, Name File,
                            <persName corresp="#p_KRW2">Komer</persName> Memos. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1966-01-08">January 8, 1966</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">Mac:</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_FYI1">FYI</gloss>:</p>
                <p>According to <persName corresp="#p_MTC1">Mann</persName>, Pat Dean said that it
                    would help enormously if we could issue a statement Monday asking our companies
                    not to import asbestos and lithium from Rhodesia. This is apparently a play to
                    back British contention of total embargo at Lagos.</p>
                <p>I agreed with Tom that a low-key State announcement to this effect would cause no
                    problem. Our imports are marginal. However, this would bother US Vanadium which
                    has a major chrom mine in Rhodesia. Vanadium fears that if it is then asked to
                    cut off chrom imports, Rhodesians will retaliate by letting the mine flood, at
                    substantial cost. Tom and I thought this contingent problem worth risking.<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d525fn2">A notation in the margin in <persName
                            corresp="#p_BMG2">Bundy</persName>’s handwriting reads: “I
                        agree.”</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">RWK</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
